<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-532-829  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 532 829.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 28 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Australia: students use computer dealing simulation. (RoyalInstitute of Technology's Treasury Training Facility, Melbourne)(financial trading)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McNamara, Sean.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   GTC (products).andO;Topic:     SimulationColleges and UniversitiesComputer-Assisted InstructionComputer industryRoyal Melbourne Institute of TechnologySecurities Transfer.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>AUSTRALIA: STUDENTS USE COMPUTER DEALING SIMULATION MELBOURNE, AUSTRALIA,1990 SEP 28 (NB) -- Students of Melbourne's Royal Institute of Technology's[RMIT] Treasury Training Facility are learning the operations of financialtrading rooms with a simulator from Australian company, GTC.andM;The system allocates students to one of ten three-person banks, each in itsown &quot;syndicate&quot; room.andP;  Over computer and phone networks, the &quot;banks&quot; can dealwith central banks, brokers, and the corporate sector [these roles are takenby instructors].andP;  Initially, only two currencies are dealt, but given time,more complex simulations involving many more currencies can be run.andP;  Thesystem keeps students informed of their profitability, with market rates andnews items also being sent to participants.andM;The system was developed around GTC's Global Training Software to meet theRMIT's requirements.andP;  A graduate is being employed to produce supportmaterials for the system, including user training modules.andP;  Wages for thegraduate will be partly offset by a grant from the National Company TrainingScheme, a part of an initiative by Federal and State governments to increaseAustralia's industrial competitiveness.andM;(Sean McNamara/19900927)</TEXT></DOC>